title: Average Difference with LDC Mean by Province, Afghanistan, 2003
name: Average Difference with LDC Mean by Province, Afghanistan, 2003
description:
The 32 provinces of Afghanistan from which data was available in 2003 show an average difference with the LDC mean ranging from  minus 61 per cent (Badghis and Uruzgan) to plus 3 per cent for Kabul province. These are substantial differences.
At the country level there are 41 usable indicators, while at the provincial level there are less (23) but 19 have been used to balance the over-influence of health and education indicators (excluded are BCG, VIT A, overall literacy and overall attendance).
Indicators used are:
 Education: male/female literacy and male/female primary school attendance
 Health: polio, DPT and measles vaccination, ARI prevalence and access to water
 Protection: child labour, child brides and birth registration
 Women: Skilled birth attendance, family planning use and antenatal care
 Other: Proportion Child Population, TFR, ARI, use of iodized salt. 
The national average in this case is minus 32 per cent, Kabul is plus 3 per cent (the mean of the LDCs) and the provinces with the worst situation, minus 60 per cent, are Badghis and Uruzgan. Three-quarters of all provinces are below the national average To place the results in an international context, the provinces with the worst situation in
Afghanistan are even worse than southern Sudan and the best province, Kabul, is as good on average, as Pakistan.
As stated, the objective of this table is to show the difference with the LDC mean; the ranking, the order of the provinces, is of less importance. The differences are very small and in one of the following paragraphs a ranking based on more and better balanced indicators will be presented.

author.source: Islamic Republic of Afghanistan, Central Statistics Organization
